                type: "content",
                title: "Introduction: Logos Refined",
                content: "We covered basic Logic in Unit 21 (The Science). Now we look at **Rhetorical Logos** (The Art).\n\nThis isn't just about 'Being Right'. It's about 'Seeming Logical'. It is the arrangement of facts to make the conclusion feel *inevitable*.\n\n**The Inevitability Frame:** You don't want the judge to think \"That's a good point.\" You want them to think \"Well, obviously. There is no other option.\" You want to close every door except the one leading to your side.\n\n**The Difference:**\n*   **Scientific Logos:** A complex data table proving climate change.\n*   **Rhetorical Logos:** \"If the ice melts, the water rises. If the water rises, the city floods. The city is flooding. Therefore, the ice is melting.\"",
                keyPoints: ["Seeming Logical", "Inevitability", "Close every door"],
                tip: "Use the word 'Therefore' (or 'Ergo'). It acts as a psychological trigger. It tells the brain 'A conclusion is coming, pay attention'."
